---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import LessonShell from "../../components/LessonShell.astro";
import Reveal from "../../components/Reveal.astro";
import { LESSONS } from "../../data/curriculum";

const lesson = LESSONS.find((l) => l.id === "code-what")!;
---

<Layout title={`${lesson.title} · Learn Claude`}>
  <main>
    <LessonShell lesson={lesson}>
      <p>
        <strong>Claude Code</strong> is the version of Claude that lives in your computer's terminal —
        the black-and-white window where you type commands. It's aimed at people who write software,
        or want to learn.
      </p>

      <h2>What makes it different from claude.ai?</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>It sees your files.</strong> Open a project folder, run <code class="inline">claude</code>, and it can read, edit, and create files in that folder.</li>
        <li><strong>It runs commands.</strong> It can install packages, run tests, start your app — with your permission.</li>
        <li><strong>It uses tools.</strong> Web searches, code search, git, agents — all from the same chat.</li>
        <li><strong>It's in your workflow.</strong> You stay in your editor and terminal; no copy-pasting between a chat website and your project.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Who is this for?</h2>
      <p>People who already work on software: developers, data scientists, SREs, students learning to code, hobbyists building side projects. If you've never written code in your life, <strong>start with Claude.ai</strong> — and come back here when you're ready to build something real.</p>

      <div class="callout">
        <strong>"The terminal" demystified.</strong> It's just an app on your computer (called Terminal on macOS,
        Windows Terminal on Windows). When you open it, you see a prompt waiting for typed commands.
        That's where Claude Code lives.
      </div>

      <h2>A taste</h2>
      <p>A typical Claude Code session might go like this:</p>
      <pre class="term" style="background: #1c1916; color: #e8dec8; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 12px; font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 0.85rem; line-height: 1.5;">
$ cd my-project
$ claude

› the app is crashing on startup, can you find why?

… reading package.json
… running npm start
… error: missing environment variable DATABASE_URL

I see — your app needs DATABASE_URL but .env doesn't have one. Want me to:
  1. Add a placeholder DATABASE_URL to .env
  2. Look up where it's used and stub it
  3. Add a startup check so the error is clearer next time?
      </pre>

      <Reveal q="Will it run scary commands without asking?">
        No. By default it asks before it edits files, runs commands, or accesses the internet. You can grant standing permission for things you trust.
      </Reveal>
      <Reveal q="Does it learn my codebase over time?">
        Each session reads what it needs. You can also write a <code class="inline">CLAUDE.md</code> file in your project with rules and context — it gets read automatically.
      </Reveal>
    </LessonShell>
  </main>
</Layout>
